## Phase 2 — Async/Await

> Every modern .NET app is async. Convert all synchronous code.

| What Changes | Before → After |
|---|---|
| Controller return types | `ActionResult` → `async Task<ActionResult>` |
| Save to DB | `SaveChanges()` → `await SaveChangesAsync()` |
| Find account | `FirstOrDefault()` → `await FirstOrDefaultAsync()` |
| Get list | `ToList()` → `await ToListAsync()` |

```csharp
// Before (blocks the thread while waiting for DB)
public ActionResult Deposit(string owner, decimal amount)
{
    var account = _context.CheckingAccounts.FirstOrDefault(a => a.Owner == owner);
    _context.SaveChanges();
    return Ok("Done");
}

// After (frees the thread — handles 100x more concurrent requests)
public async Task<ActionResult> Deposit(string owner, decimal amount)
{
    var account = await _context.CheckingAccounts.FirstOrDefaultAsync(a => a.Owner == owner);
    await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    return Ok("Done");
}
```

> **Interview Q**: "Why async?" → "It frees the thread while waiting for I/O, letting the server handle thousands of concurrent requests instead of blocking."

