## Phase 4 — Authentication & Authorization

> No bank lets anonymous users access accounts.

| Task | Skill Learned |
|---|---|
| Add ASP.NET Core Identity | Built-in `/register`, `/login`, `/refresh` for free |
| Add `User` model linked to accounts | One-to-many relationships |
| Add `[Authorize]` to banking endpoints | Token-based auth |
| Users can only access their own accounts | Claims-based authorization |

> **Not** manual JWT generation — Identity API Endpoints handle all of that automatically in .NET 8+.

---

## Phase 5 — Transfers, Transaction History & Pagination

> Real banking features that separate toy projects from impressive ones.

| Task | Skill Learned |
|---|---|
| `POST /api/Bank/transfer` (atomic, both sides succeed or both fail) | EF Core Transactions |
| `Transaction` model: Id, AccountId, Type, Amount, Timestamp | Audit Trail Design |
| Auto-log every deposit, withdrawal, and transfer | Event tracking |
| `GET /api/Bank/transactions?page=1&pageSize=20` | Pagination |
| `GET /api/v2/Bank/accounts` | API Versioning |

```csharp
// Pagination — Skip/Take pattern
var transactions = await _context.Transactions
    .Where(t => t.AccountId == accountId)
    .OrderByDescending(t => t.Timestamp)
    .Skip((page - 1) * pageSize)
    .Take(pageSize)
    .ToListAsync();
```

---

## Phase 6 — Minimal APIs + SQL Server

> Learn the modern API style and upgrade to a production database.

| Task | Skill Learned |
|---|---|
| Build 2-3 endpoints using Minimal APIs alongside controllers | Modern API style |
| Upgrade SQLite → SQL Server Express (via `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.SqlServer`) | Production database |
| Add a new EF Core migration for SQL Server | Database migration |
| Use connection string from [appsettings.json](file:///Users/rajkushwaha/Desktop/develop/dotnet-projects/web_app_Csharp/appsettings.json) / environment variables | Configuration management |

```csharp
// Minimal API — same endpoint, zero controller boilerplate
app.MapGet("/api/accounts/{id}", async (int id, BankContext db) =>
{
    var account = await db.CheckingAccounts.FindAsync(id);
    return account is not null ? Results.Ok(account) : Results.NotFound();
});
```

> **Interview Q**: "When would you use Minimal APIs vs Controllers?" → "Minimal APIs for simple, focused endpoints (microservices). Controllers for complex APIs with many endpoints, filters, and shared logic."

